cel, Andre, Donat, Emile, Francois, Jacques, Laurent, Pierre, Rolande.","Altered form of French   Mallet  , reflecting the Canadian and American French practice of sounding the final <i>-t</i>. Compare   Mallett  .","English: rare variant of   Mallett  ."]},{"name":"Mal","meanings":["Slovenian: nickname for a physically small man, from <i>mal</i> ‘small, little’.","French (mainly Nord): nickname from <i>mal</i> ‘bad’ (from Latin <i>malus</i>).","Indian (northern states): variant of   Mall  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":17,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas Mallet was born in 1365, in Enmore Castle, Somerset, England. He had at least 2 sons and 2 daughters with Elizabeth Trivett. He died in 1416, in Enmore, Somerset, England, at the age of 51."},"et":{"1365–1416":"1365–1416","1349–1373":"1349–1373","1370–Male":"1370–Surnud","1399–Female":"1399–Surnud","1399–Male":"1399–Surnud","1423–1473":"1423–1473","1349":"1349","1423":"1423","1399":"1399","1365":"1365","1473":"1473","1373":"1373","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","141